(
  'Best Restaurants in Calvia: A 2026 Food Lover''s Guide',
  'best-restaurants-calvia-2026-food-guide',
  'From traditional Mallorcan cuisine to world-class seafood, Calvia offers a dining scene that rivals anywhere on the island. Here are the restaurants you need to try.',
  '<p>Calvia has quietly become one of Mallorca''s most exciting dining destinations. While Palma attracts most of the culinary attention, Calvia''s restaurants offer something increasingly rare: exceptional food in settings that have not yet been overwhelmed by mass tourism.</p>

<h2>Traditional Mallorcan Cuisine</h2>
<p>Ca''s Maians in Calvia village remains the gold standard for authentic Mallorcan cooking. Tucked down a narrow stone lane, this family-run restaurant has been serving tumbet, frit mallorqui, and slow-roasted suckling pig for three generations. The terrace overlooking the church square is one of the most charming dining spots in the municipality. Reserve ahead for weekend dinners.</p>
<p>For a more contemporary take on island traditions, Es Celler in Es Capdella transforms classic recipes with modern technique. Their deconstructed sobrassada with local honey and crispy bread has become a signature dish worth driving for.</p>

<h2>Seafood Along the Coast</h2>
<p>Illeta in Portals Nous delivers pristine seafood in an elegant beachside setting. The catch of the day, simply grilled with local olive oil and Mallorcan sea salt, is consistently outstanding. Their rice dishes, particularly the arros brut and seafood paella, are among the best on the southwest coast.</p>
<p>For a more casual seafood experience, Chiringuito in Peguera serves the freshest pescado frito and patatas bravas on the beach. The sunset views from the terrace make even a simple plate of grilled sardines feel special.</p>

<h2>International Fine Dining</h2>
<p>Calvia has attracted several internationally trained chefs in recent years. Neni at the Bikini Hotel in Magaluf brings Middle Eastern and Southeast Asian flavors to the table with a Mediterranean twist. The sharing-plate format encourages exploration, and the rooftop setting is spectacular.</p>
<p>Ritzi in Puerto Portals has long been the area''s premier Italian dining room. Handmade pasta, imported ingredients, and impeccable service justify the premium prices. Their truffle tagliatelle is a perennial favorite among regulars.</p>

<h2>Where the Locals Eat</h2>
<p>The true test of a restaurant is whether locals choose it when they are not entertaining visitors. Sa Societat in Calvia village, Can Torrat in Portals, and Bar Parisien in Santa Ponsa consistently draw neighborhood regulars for their honest cooking, reasonable prices, and welcoming atmosphere. These are the places where you will hear more Catalan than English, and the food is all the better for it.</p>',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/67468/pexels-photo-67468.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1260&h=750&dpr=2',
  '361ed32d-aa76-486c-89b1-c9c25fcf8ba8',
