(
  'Calvia''s Best Tapas Bars: A Local''s Walking Tour',
  'calvia-best-tapas-bars-local-walking-tour',
  'Skip the tourist traps. This insider tapas trail through Calvia and its coastal towns leads to the most authentic bites, from jamón ibérico to patatas bravas.',
  '<p>The tapas culture in Calvia is alive and thriving, but you have to know where to look. The best tapas bars are not on the main tourist strips; they are tucked into village side streets and local neighborhoods where the quality-to-price ratio is unbeatable.</p>

<h2>Starting in Calvia Village</h2>
<p>Begin at Bar Can Tomeu on the village square. This no-frills bar serves some of the best pa amb oli on the island: thick slices of rustic bread rubbed with ripe tomato, drizzled with local olive oil, and topped with jamón serrano and Mahón cheese. Pair it with a cana of local draft beer for under five euros. The terrace fills with locals on Saturday mornings and the atmosphere is wonderfully unhurried.</p>

<h2>Down to Santa Ponsa</h2>
<p>A fifteen-minute drive brings you to Santa Ponsa, where Bodega del Mar offers an outstanding selection of pintxos. The anchovy and roasted pepper combination is exceptional, and their croquetas de jamón are crispy on the outside with a molten, intensely flavored interior. The wine list focuses on Mallorcan and mainland Spanish producers, with several available by the glass.</p>
<p>Just around the corner, Taberna Sa Cova is known for its grilled octopus with smoked paprika and their generous portions of patatas bravas with both brava and alioli sauces.</p>

<h2>The Portals Strip</h2>
<p>Puerto Portals is known for its upscale dining, but tucked behind the marina you will find Tapa Negra, a standing-room tapas bar that attracts yacht crews and local residents alike. Their menu changes daily based on market availability. The gambas al ajillo and montaditos of sobrassada with quince are consistent standouts.</p>

<h2>Evening in Peguera</h2>
<p>End your tour in Peguera at La Taberna, where the tapas take on a creative twist. Think duck confit croquetas, grilled provolone with sun-dried tomatoes, and a remarkable anchovies-and-burrata combination that keeps people coming back. The informal atmosphere and reasonable prices make this a perfect final stop.</p>

<h2>Tips for Tapas Success</h2>
<p>Eat when locals eat: lunch around 2pm, tapas from 7:30pm. Do not rush; the point is to linger. Order two or three dishes at a time and add more as you go. Say hello in Catalan (bon dia) and you will instantly receive warmer service. Most importantly, follow the crowds: if a tapas bar is full of Spanish speakers, you are in the right place.</p>',
