(
  'The Complete Guide to Calvia''s Weekly Markets and Local Shops',
  'complete-guide-calvia-weekly-markets-local-shops',
  'From the Monday morning market in Calvia village to artisan boutiques in Portals, here is your guide to shopping local across the municipality.',
  '<p>One of the best ways to experience authentic Calvia is through its markets and independent shops. While the coastal towns have their share of international brands, the real character lies in the weekly street markets, family-run businesses, and artisan workshops that have served the community for generations.</p>

<h2>Weekly Markets</h2>
<p>The Monday morning market in Calvia village is the municipality''s oldest and most traditional. Stretching along the main streets from 8am to 1pm, vendors sell fresh produce from Mallorcan farms, local cheeses, cured meats, olives, almonds, and seasonal fruits. The non-food section offers leather goods, ceramics, and textiles. Arrive early for the best selection and a more relaxed atmosphere before the crowds build.</p>
<p>Santa Ponsa hosts its market on Saturdays, offering a mix of local produce and artisan goods. The organic produce stalls have expanded significantly in recent years, reflecting growing demand for locally sourced, chemical-free food.</p>
<p>Peguera''s Tuesday market is smaller but has a loyal following for its excellent selection of Mallorcan preserves, honeys, and handmade soaps. The surrounding streets are worth exploring for their independent boutiques and art galleries.</p>

<h2>Artisan and Specialty Shops</h2>
<p>Teixits Riera near Calvia village has been weaving traditional Mallorcan tongue-of-flame fabric since 1854. Their shop sells table linens, cushion covers, and bags in the distinctive zigzag pattern that has become a symbol of the island. It makes for a meaningful souvenir with genuine cultural significance.</p>
<p>Oli de Calvia is a cooperative that produces award-winning extra virgin olive oil from the ancient groves surrounding the village. Tours of the press are available during harvest season, October through December, and the shop sells the full range of their production year-round.</p>

<h2>Food Shops Worth Visiting</h2>
<p>Ca''n Garanya in Calvia village is a traditional colmado, a Mallorcan general store, stocking locally cured sobrassada, Mahón cheese, wines from Binissalem, and pantry essentials. La Panaderia in Es Capdella bakes ensaimadas, the island''s beloved spiral pastry, using a generations-old recipe.</p>

<h2>Supporting Local Economy</h2>
<p>Every purchase at a local market or independent shop directly supports Calvia''s community. These businesses employ local residents, preserve traditional crafts, and maintain the authentic character that makes the municipality special. Choosing local over international chains is one of the most impactful things visitors and residents alike can do.</p>',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2749481/pexels-photo-2749481.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1260&h=750&dpr=2',
