(
  'Top 15 Things to Do in Calvia: Activities for Every Season',
  'top-15-things-to-do-calvia-every-season',
  'Whether you are visiting in summer or winter, Calvia offers far more than beaches. Here are 15 activities that showcase the best of this Mallorcan municipality.',
  '<p>Calvia is Mallorca''s most diverse municipality. Within its boundaries you will find dramatic mountain scenery, over 30 beaches, historic villages, world-class golf courses, and a coastline that ranges from quiet coves to vibrant resort areas. Here are fifteen ways to experience the best of it, whatever time of year you visit.</p>

<h2>Year-Round Activities</h2>
<p><strong>1. Hike the Calvia to Es Capdella Trail.</strong> This moderate 8-kilometer route connects two of the municipality''s most charming villages through olive groves, pine forests, and hillside terraces. The views of the Tramuntana mountains are exceptional, and the trail is well-marked and accessible for reasonably fit walkers.</p>
<p><strong>2. Explore Calvia Village.</strong> The historic capital of the municipality is often overlooked by coastal visitors. The 13th-century church of Sant Joan Baptista, the narrow stone streets, and the excellent local restaurants make it worthy of a half-day visit.</p>
<p><strong>3. Visit the Katmandu Park.</strong> This family entertainment complex in Magaluf features an upside-down house, mini golf, VR experiences, and water rides. It is one of Mallorca''s best attractions for families with children.</p>

<h2>Spring and Summer</h2>
<p><strong>4. Swim at Cala Mago.</strong> One of Mallorca''s most beautiful small beaches, Cala Mago is reached by a short path through pine woods. The turquoise water is crystal clear, and the surrounding cliffs provide natural shade in the afternoon.</p>
<p><strong>5. Snorkel the Malgrats Islands Marine Reserve.</strong> The protected waters around these small islands host seahorses, octopus, grouper, and vibrant underwater meadows. Several operators in Santa Ponsa offer guided snorkeling trips.</p>
<p><strong>6. Golf at Santa Ponsa.</strong> Three championship courses make Calvia one of the Mediterranean''s premier golf destinations. The Santa Ponsa I course, designed by Folco Nardi, offers mountain and sea views on nearly every hole.</p>
<p><strong>7. Sunset Kayaking from Peguera.</strong> Paddle along the coastline as the sun sets behind the mountains. Guided tours include stops at sea caves and hidden coves inaccessible by land.</p>

<h2>Autumn and Winter</h2>
<p><strong>8. Olive Harvest Experience.</strong> October through December, several farms in the Calvia hills welcome visitors to participate in the traditional olive harvest. It is hard, satisfying work rewarded with fresh-pressed oil tastings.</p>
<p><strong>9. Mountain Biking in the Tramuntana Foothills.</strong> Cooler temperatures make autumn and winter ideal for cycling. The trails between Calvia village and Puigpunyent offer challenging terrain with extraordinary scenery.</p>
<p><strong>10-15: More Adventures Await.</strong> Complete your Calvia experience with a wine tasting in the Binissalem region, a cooking class at a local restaurant, a boat trip to the Dragonera island nature reserve, a visit to the Bendinat Castle, a cycling tour along the coastal road, or simply a long lunch at a village square restaurant watching the world go by.</p>

<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>A rental car provides the most flexibility for exploring Calvia thoroughly. However, the TIB bus network connects all major towns within the municipality, and cycling is increasingly practical thanks to improved bike lanes on coastal roads.</p>',
