(
  'Living in Calvia: An Expat''s Honest Guide to Mallorca''s Best-Kept Secret',
  'living-in-calvia-expat-guide-mallorca',
  'Thinking about moving to Calvia? From housing and healthcare to schools and community life, here is everything you need to know about relocating to this Mallorcan municipality.',
  '<p>Calvia attracts more international residents each year, drawn by its combination of natural beauty, excellent infrastructure, international schools, and a quality of life that is difficult to match elsewhere in Europe. Having lived here for several years, here is an honest assessment of what daily life in Calvia is actually like.</p>

<h2>Housing and Neighborhoods</h2>
<p>Calvia offers distinct living environments. Santa Ponsa and Peguera provide apartment and townhouse living with good amenities, supermarkets, and beach access. Costa de la Calma is quieter and more residential, popular with families. Bendinat and Sol de Mallorca attract those seeking luxury villas with sea views. Calvia village itself offers traditional Mallorcan stone houses at prices significantly lower than the coast.</p>
<p>Rental prices vary dramatically. A two-bedroom apartment in Santa Ponsa starts around 1,200 euros per month, while coastal villas can exceed 5,000. Purchase prices have risen steadily, but Calvia remains more accessible than Palma''s old town or the Andratx coast.</p>

<h2>Healthcare</h2>
<p>The public healthcare system is excellent. The Centre de Salut in Santa Ponsa provides primary care, and the Son Espases university hospital in Palma is a twenty-minute drive. Private healthcare is also readily available, with several clinics in the municipality offering services in multiple languages.</p>

<h2>Education</h2>
<p>Families are well served with options. The Balearic International College and Agora International School provide English-language education following British and international curricula. Spanish and Catalan public schools are of good quality, and several offer bilingual programs. The international school community provides a ready-made social network for newly arrived families.</p>

<h2>Daily Life</h2>
<p>Supermarket shopping is easy with Mercadona, Eroski, and Lidl all present. The climate allows outdoor living for most of the year. The international community is welcoming, with social groups, sports clubs, and cultural organizations that make integration straightforward. Spanish bureaucracy can be challenging, but hiring a gestor, a local administrative consultant, smooths most processes.</p>

<h2>The Honest Downsides</h2>
<p>Seasonal fluctuation is real. Some coastal areas feel very quiet from November through March. Summer traffic on the coastal road can be frustrating. Learning Spanish, and ideally some Catalan, is important for full integration. The cost of living has risen significantly in recent years, though it remains lower than northern European cities.</p>

<h2>The Verdict</h2>
<p>Calvia offers an exceptional quality of life for those willing to engage with both the international and local communities. The combination of natural beauty, infrastructure, climate, and cultural richness makes it one of the Mediterranean''s most livable municipalities.</p>',
